*“You are an expert in experimentation, statistics, and data science, with deep applied knowledge in A/B testing, causal inference, and optimization frameworks used in both digital and assisted channels (telecom, e-commerce, and customer engagement platforms). I want you to create a comprehensive 50-page Advanced Experimentation Playbook that will serve as both a training guide and a reference book for senior data scientists and experimentation leaders.

Content Requirements

The playbook must be structured into detailed chapters with use-case-driven explanations and should include the following:
	1.	Foundations of Experimentation
	•	Principles of causal inference, hypothesis testing, and experimentation design.
	•	Common pitfalls and biases in experiments.
	2.	Parametric vs. Non-Parametric Tests
	•	When to use which test.
	•	Test selection matrix based on metric type (binary, continuous, count, ratio).
	•	Worked examples with calculations.
	3.	Metric & Data-Type Driven Test Selection
	•	Primary vs. secondary KPIs.
	•	Guardrail metrics.
	•	Examples: conversion rate, engagement, transaction time.
	4.	Sampling & Representation
	•	Randomization strategies.
	•	Sample size calculation (frequentist and Bayesian approaches).
	•	Dealing with skewed populations and stratification.
	5.	Matched Control Group Creation
	•	Techniques for building matched controls in pilot/baseline scenarios.
	•	Use of propensity score matching and synthetic controls.
	6.	Bayesian Approaches & Sequential Testing
	•	Bayesian inference in experiments.
	•	Dynamic decision boundaries.
	•	Practical advantages over frequentist methods.
	7.	Experimentation in Real-World Business Contexts
	•	Assisted channels (e.g., agent-led sales).
	•	Digital channels (web/app recommendations, personalization).
	•	Telecom case studies (e.g., Verizon Gridwall device recommendations, VZEngage).
	8.	Optimization Beyond A/B Testing
	•	Multi-armed bandits.
	•	Adaptive experimentation.
	•	Uplift modeling.
	9.	Experimentation Governance & Culture
	•	Guardrails for scaling experimentation.
	•	Common organizational challenges.
	•	Best practices for reporting and decision-making.

Format Requirements
	•	Minimum 50 pages of detailed, well-structured content.
	•	Include formulas, flowcharts, and tabular decision frameworks.
	•	Include at least 3–5 real-world use cases (e.g., Verizon B360 Gridwall A/B test, VZEngage uplift experiment, assisted-channel digital summary pilot).
	•	Deliver in DOCX, PDF, and Markdown formats.
	•	Appendices should include:
	•	Experimentation checklist
	•	Statistical formula reference sheet
	•	Sample experiment design templates

Tone & Depth
	•	Written for experienced data scientists and analytics leaders.
	•	No shallow overviews — must include deep technical rigor while being business-contextualized.
	•	Blend theory + application + case studies.

Now, create this playbook step by step, ensuring structure, depth, and applied rigor.”
